%% Diagram: How libuv emulates a completion API on top of readiness epoll
%% Type: sequence
sequenceDiagram
    participant App as User code
    participant Loop as Event loop thread
    participant Kern as Linux kernel (epoll)
    participant Sock as Non-blocking socket fd

    App->>Loop: uv_read_start(stream, alloc_cb, read_cb)
    Loop->>Kern: epoll_ctl(ADD, fd, EPOLLIN, level-triggered)
    Note over Loop,Kern: Registration may be batched via io_uring<br/>(always-on as of v1.50.0)
    Loop->>Kern: epoll_pwait(timeout = next_due_timer_ms)
    Note over Kern: Loop thread blocks; CPU is yielded
    Sock-->>Kern: TCP segments arrive, fd readable
    Kern-->>Loop: epoll_pwait returns: fd EPOLLIN
    Loop->>App: alloc_cb(handle, suggested_size, &buf)
    Loop->>Sock: read(fd, buf.base, buf.len) — non-blocking
    Sock-->>Loop: bytes (or EAGAIN, or 0 = EOF)
    Loop->>App: read_cb(stream, nread, &buf)
    Note over Loop,App: User sees a completion-style callback,<br/>even though Linux only signalled readiness.
